title: [0.1.2] Item withdrawal from a terminal does not work with some items
body:
So, I'm having a hard time tracking down what the bug is exactly... 

[Here's a screenshot](http://puu.sh/nUC2O/c076424621.jpg) of the items I literally cannot take out of the terminal... their NBT has been reset too (for the BuildCraft Redstone Board. That was a programmed board before placing it in there).

The spawn egg I put in there was also not blank - but now it is... however the entity's spawn type is stored in Metadata rather than NBT, so I'm not really sure? Seems like somewhere there's not an itemstack.copy() where there should be ;D

EDIT: confirmed that with one of my (CrissCross's) pouches with items in it, when I tossed it in my terminal, all the NBT Tags (one per item stored) were erased.

title: [0.1.2] Terminal GUI is (randomly) inaccessible until re-placed
body:
See title: sometimes (on random intervals as far as I can tell) the GUI of the Terminal will not open, no matter how many times I right-click. I've had this happen when returning to it after visiting the nether in a test world (however the terminal and controller **were both chunk-loaded the entire time**), and it just occurred again right after creating a whole new storage setup. As soon as the controller booted, the terminal had to be broken and re-placed.

By the way - I'm super thrilled with this mod! :D I'm only posting bug-reports because you can't fix bugs you don't know about! Keep up the good work, I'll let you know if I find anything else!

title: [Suggestion] Terminal GUI Sorting Options
body:
Thought it was basically the only thing that makes me still miss Applied Energistics for its basic purposes: alternative sorting methods for the Terminal's GUI. Not sure if you want to take a look at JEI's code to see how he does it, but the biggest ones to me that would be cool are:
1. Quantity (already currently used)
2. Alphabetical
3. ModID (this one is most used by me, honestly) - starting with Minecraft first (like JEI)

0.1.3 is great by the way!! Waiting for BC to update to resolve a recurring crash on my server, then I'm tossing it on there! :D

title: Drive Bays do not drop held drives when destroyed
body: When breaking a Drive Bay in survival mode, the Drive Bay block drops, but all the drives that were held in the bay are destroyed.

title: All blocks break instantly with any tool
body: Ideally, they should take 1-2 seconds to break and require a pickaxe.

title: Item conversion in the interface
body:
If you place an item in the output slot, then add a different item into the configuration spot for the same output slot, you can then place in any of the configured item into the system or input slots and it will be converted into the output item.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8d8hoUFGcfc
Here is a video of the bug in action, it's really quick.

title: we need a crafting terminal
body: crafting terminal is neat

title: Shift doubleclick does not work for mass insert
body: Would be a useful feature. It's a pain slowly inserting a lot of a single item.

title: Extra slot in the terminal that allows the player to dump the contents of a drive
body:
![](http://i.imgur.com/CIQnKwM.png)

Basically, I have a bunch of shit in this drive, and I want to put it in the system without manually taking it all out and putting it back in.

title: Add in-game documentation
body:
Make it look like a futuristic tablet thing, that you get automatically upon finding or crafting a processor thing.

I'm thinking something similar to the Open Computers or TIS-3D documentation would be good for this mod, if you've seen those. 

https://github.com/MightyPirates/TIS-3D/tree/master-MC1.8.9/src/main/java/li/cil/tis3d/client/manual

title: [1.9.4] Feature request-expose RF req to run in config
body: I really like the simplicity of this mod.   Would it be possible to expose the systems RF req in the config and allow it to be adjusted for balance in a pack or on a server?

title: Fluid compatibility
body: If possible, could you add a feature for the insertion and removal of fluids to the drives? If that doesn't sit well, what about specifically partitioning drives for solids or fluids? Another idea would be to have an additional drives (with similar capacities) specifically for fluids.

title: Satellite location textures won't update until clicked on
body:
I have a satellite location that's accessing the inventory of my main base remotely. However, whenever power is lost to it, or restored to it, the textures don't update to reflect their loss / gain of power until I right click on them. It's a small issue because all of the functionality is as intended, just a visual issue.

[Loss](https://youtu.be/8CaXAFIU9ns)

[Gain](https://youtu.be/zZZAMgwil00)

title: Auto Crafting
body:
I know this mod is supposed to be minimalistic, but this is actually the best alternative to Applied Energistics 2 for 1.8/1.9 and can easily replace it, like JEI and NEI. So, why not add autocrafting? (I liked more the way autocrafting worked in AE1)

Keep up the good work, this mod is very fancy!

title: Wireless range extender
body:
I think that the wireless transmitters range is OK, but if you try to use your wireless terminal far away your main storage, e.g. in your mine, you would need two wireless terminals, one bound to the "upper" transmitter and one for the mine. The solution written on the wiki (controller+receiver+transmitter) didn't work for me, because I the wireless terminal can only be bound to one transmitter.

A solution could be a new block, the range extender, which does nothing but copies the id of the transmitter whose range you want to extend for another 64 blocks or something. This would also need a controller and power source, but would make reaching your storage easier. 

Another solution could be that when your system only consist a controller+receiver+transmitter, it works as an extender and shares the same id as what it's extending, until you connect an interface or a drive bay. After that it becomes a different station.

title: Auto restock crafting grid
body:
In AE2, clicking the output of the crafting grid (when using a Crafting Terminal) would restock the crafting grid, unless there were no components in the system to craft the target item, or it was manually cleared.  In CoPo, the JEI + button has to be used each time, unless I want a full stack of the target item or something like that.  If I want to craft, for example, 9 of a given item, it's quite inconvenient.

I can manually place multiple components on the Terminal's crafting grid, but using Shift+click on the JEI "+" button only sets up for a single craft, and often transfers some other item to my inventory that I don't want.

title: Add EU support
body:
AE2 had an Energy Acceptor (http://ae-mod.info/Energy-Acceptor/) for converting different types of energy into a form that AE2 could use, so why not something similar for CoPo?  afaik, RotaryCraft hasn't been updated past 1.7.10, but IndustrialCraft 2 (https://minecraft.curseforge.com/projects/industrial-craft) and Mekanism (http://aidancbrady.com/mekanism/download/) have 1.10.2 versions, and there's also Tesla that some users might be interested in, which is only for MC 1.9+ (personally, I'm most interested in support for IC2).

Note: it wasn't documented, and might not have been intentional, but AE2's ME Controller could connect to IC2 cables directly and accept power that way without needing the separate Energy Acceptor in between.  IDK whether the controller accepted the other power types that way.

title: Multiple boots of an identical network can increase the power consumption
body:
I have the following blocks in my CoPo network:
1. a controller (32 T/t)
2. a terminal (4 T/t)
3. a memory bay (with a total of 9 KiB of memory at the moment, though afaik it draws 4 T/t regardless of how much memory is installed)
4. a drive bay with eight 4 MiB drives (8 T/t for the bay + 2 T/t per drive = 24 T/t)
That should be 64 T/t, right?

When I open the world (single-player), the controller shows a usage of 32 T/t before powering it (presumably since it hasn't scanned the network yet).  Once I power it up, the usage goes up to 64 T/t.  Okay so far.  However, when I turn off the power (in case it matters, I'm using a Forestry Electrical Engine upgraded with two "Electrical Boost II" (for a total of 100 RF/t output capability) and an Advanced Charging Battery in it), let the controller drain, then power it up again, the usage becomes 88 T/t.  Wait, what?  Where did the extra 24 T/t come from?  

If I have it in a backwards "L" shape to prevent multiple paths from the controller to other blocks (terminal above it, memory bay below, drive bay to the west of the memory bay, and engine to the east of the controller), it stays at 88 T/t even with repeated boots.  However, if I move the terminal to the west of the controller (to make a square shape), it can go up to 92 T/t.

In the discussion it is stated that Forge needs to fix their dimension type handling to tolerate mod removal/changes which would help in the future to avoid problems like that. title: Optical Receivers always use the closest APN source, even if it's broken
body:
E.g. if you have three optical receivers, one bound to a system, one far away, and one between (but closer to the second), then the second and last don't work, as the second tries to connect to the last and vice-versa. None of them connect to the system itself.

APNs need to consider whether or not a source is erroring.

title: Add the ability to use Embers power to run the system
body:
I realize most packs have at least some tech in them and this is a tech themed system. However, to truly differentiate yourself from other tech based storage systems, it would be nice to see you allow the Embers mod power system to work with your system by default without the need for another mod or something.

To be perfectly honest, I've been wishing someone could make a magical themed storage system that would do the same functionality seen in AE2, Refined Storage, and CoPo; but with that would fit better into a nearly completely magic based modpack.

I don't expect such a huge thing from CoPo, but accepting other power than just tech based RF, Tesla, Forge, EU, or Joules would be a decent compromise.

title: Creative Drive
body:
Basically just a drive that will give out infinite copies of anything put in it when in Whitelist mode. Other modes it just acts like a drive with infinite storage. Can't be put into or taken out of a drive bay by a survival player (unless a config option is set, to allow for packs like Infinity, which I dislike but don't really have a reason to prevent from working)

My use case is a system at the spawn on a server containing lots of decorative blocks. (See: elytra/Fondue6#5)

title: Markdown render issue: text wrapping and line breaks
body:
Documented in:
- Minecraft 1.12.1
- Forge 14.22.0.2474
- Correlated 2.0

Issue:
When Markdown text-wrapping is used, the Markdown renderer fails to add a space properly; even if there is a space in the Markdown document.

Image example:
![](https://cdn.discordapp.com/attachments/290916642232336394/381663454127456271/image.png)
(can be seen at "pearlsnear", "theycan", and "NOTUNDER"; there are line breaks at those points in the Markdown that have spaces at the beginning of each line, but the space isn't rendered)
